title: Putin Says Russia Is Battling ‘Strange’ Western Elites
description: Ahead of U.S. elections, the Russian leader sounded like some right-wing Westerners, saying his fight is not with those in the West who hold “traditional values.”

title: OSCE Election Observers Warn of Republican Election Deniers
description: Attempts by candidates to discredit the integrity of the vote have “snowballed enormously” since the 2020 election, the head of the observation mission said.

title: G.O.P. Senator’s Report on Covid Origins Suggests Lab Leak, but Offers Little New Evidence
description: The report, signed by Senator Richard Burr, foreshadows a new wave of political wrangling over Covid’s origins if Republicans gain control of the House or Senate.

title: Memorials for 2 Young Women Killed in Iran Galvanize Protests
description: For a second day in a row, tens of thousands of demonstrators protested across Iran against the country’s authoritarian clerical rule. The government response on Thursday was again deadly.

title: Your Friday Briefing: The U.S. Economy Grew, Slowly
description: Plus the war in Ukraine may boost clean energy and investigations into Chinese outposts overseas.

title: Iraqi Parliament Approves New Government After Yearlong Delay
description: The installation of a new prime minister and cabinet ends a long-running political deadlock, but perpetuates a system plagued by corruption and dysfunction.

title: With Economy Reeling From Ukraine War, Egypt Secures $3 Billion I.M.F. Loan
description: The local currency had tumbled against the dollar, and food and energy prices soared in the wake of Russia’s February invasion of Ukraine, adding to the struggles of millions of Egyptians.

title: U.S. Program Aims to Keep Sensitive Weapons in Ukraine
description: Portable, lethal and high-tech munitions like Stinger and Javelin missiles are a focus of a monitoring program operating from the embassy in Kyiv.

title: Why Russia Stole Potemkin’s Bones From Ukraine
description: The 18th-century general and lover of Catherine the Great helped conquer Ukraine and looms large in the version of history the Kremlin uses to justify the war.

title: Israeli-Lebanese Maritime Deal Marks a Milestone, With Limitations
description: The U.S.-brokered deal has stirred fierce debate in Israel between some who view it as an achievement and others as a dangerous capitulation.

title: UK Tells Schools They Can’t Ban Afro Hairstyles
description: School rules about what styles are allowed that mostly affect Black and mixed-race children are likely to be illegal, a government rights commission said.

title: Somalia Asks US to Step Up Drone Strikes Against Qaeda-Linked Fighters
description: A new administration in Somalia has launched an offensive against Al Shabab, which are also facing an uprising from local militias.

title: Pentagon’s Strategy Says China and Russia Pose More Dangerous Challenges
description: A new document describes the military’s response to a new era in broad terms and guides Pentagon policy and budget decisions, but it lacks details.

title: Putin begins a high-profile address amid fears that he is escalating the war.
Foxconn’s Big iPhone Plant Hit by China’s Latest Covid Lockdown
description: An outbreak in Zhengzhou has sent an unknown number of workers at the city’s Foxconn plant into quarantine. It’s a bad time of year for output of iPhones to slow down.

title: The Climate’s Improved Future
description: The world has made real progress on climate change.

title: Putin Expected to Lay Out Views on Foreign Affairs in Speech
description: The annual speech is often a rare moment of unscripted questioning from independent analysts and journalists.

title: China’s Chest-Thumping Nationalism Now Goes Too Far, Movement’s Godfather Says
description: Wang Xiaodong, who helped pioneer China’s nationalist bravado, now fends off criticisms of being too moderate, too cozy with the West, even a traitor. “They’ve forgotten,” he said, “I created them.”

title: Europe’s Energy Crisis Is Sending Leaders to Africa for Help
description: Officials from Algeria to Mozambique say they hope to take advantage of an abrupt change in a long-unequal relationship.

title: Mexico’s Senate Votes to Eliminate Daylight Saving Time
description: The measure, if signed by the president, would not affect the northern region of the country along the U.S. border.

title: Your Thursday Briefing
description: Support for Ukraine wavers.

title: Putin Wants to Divide Ukrainians. Mykolaiv Is a Test Case.
description: In a battered city on Ukraine’s southern coast, salt water runs from the taps and electricity is sporadic. Residents curse Russia, but also express frustration with their own leaders.

title: War in Ukraine Likely to Speed, Not Slow, Shift to Clean Energy, I.E.A. Says
description: While some nations are burning more coal this year in response to natural-gas shortages spurred by Russia’s invasion of Ukraine, that effect is expected to be short-lived.

title: Australian Judge Orders New Trial in Rape Case That Shook Capital
description: A former parliamentary staffer is accused of raping a colleague in the defense minister’s office. The judge said a juror had brought an article on sexual assault cases into the jury room against her instructions.

title: Biden Faces New Challenges With Coalition on Ukraine Support
description: The domestic and international consensus has shown signs of fraying as midterm elections loom in the United States and Europeans face the prospect of a cold winter.
